Ladies, you must do these! 

Strengthening the posterior chain ain’t always about glutes 😏 

This is one of my faves- “back cable crossovers” primarily targeting the muscles of the upper back and rear deltoids. Performing this exercise can help improve overall upper body strength, promote better posture, and enhance shoulder stability. It also aids in developing well-rounded back muscles and can be beneficial for individuals aiming to improve their overall upper body aesthetics and functional strength…. And and andddd who doesn’t like a good looking back???? 

Try it out 4 sets of 15-20 🔥

Anyways, one thing about me when I prep clients: I always ask if having a ‘Partner’ is an issue before I match anyone together. I’ve seen amazing results with my clients who are partnered up versus going solo. I do understand that some people prefer to train solo, and that’s perfectly fine.

A few benefits of having a workout partner:

✨Motivation: Exercising with a partner can provide motivation and encouragement, helping you stay committed to your fitness routine.

✨Accountability: Having a workout partner can hold you accountable for your gym sessions, making it less likely for you to skip workouts.

✨Increased intensity: Partner workouts can push you to work harder and challenge yourself, leading to better results.

✨Spotting: Having a partner can make it safer to lift heavy weights as they can spot you during exercises like bench presses.

✨Variety: Partner workouts can introduce variety to your routine, as you can engage in partner exercises or drills that you might not do alone.

✨Social interaction: Working out with a partner can be a social and enjoyable experience, making your workout more fun.

✨Feedback and form correction: Your partner can provide feedback on your form and technique, helping you avoid injuries and improve your performance.

✨Competitive edge: Friendly competition can make your workouts more engaging and push you to achieve your fitness goals.

✨Partner stretches: Partners can assist in stretching exercises, enhancing your flexibility.

✨Emotional support: Having someone to share your fitness journey with can provide emotional support and reduce stress.

And always remember that partner workouts are most effective when both individuals have similar fitness goals and commitment levels.

Stretching 😫 is soooo important to do as we get older. I’ll be 34 for the next 100 years and i plan on stretching as often as possible. My good friend @bodyxgii been showing me some guidance and helping me on my journey!

Take a look at why stretching is important as we age 🥹: 

✨Flexibility: Stretching helps maintain and improve flexibility in muscles and joints, which can decrease as we get older. This flexibility is essential for maintaining a full range of motion in daily activities.

✨Injury Prevention: Regular stretching can reduce the risk of muscle strains and injuries, as it keeps muscles and tendons more pliable and less prone to tearing.

✨Posture: Stretching can help improve posture by releasing tension in tight muscles, which can lead to better spinal alignment and reduced discomfort.

✨Pain Relief: Stretching can alleviate aches and pains associated with conditions like arthritis or stiffness from prolonged sitting, providing relief and improving overall comfort.

✨Circulation: Stretching can enhance blood flow and circulation, which is crucial for supplying oxygen and nutrients to the muscles and tissues, aiding in recovery and reducing muscle fatigue.

✨Stress Reduction: Stretching promotes relaxation and reduces stress by releasing endorphins, the body’s natural feel-good hormones.

Overall, regular stretching as we age can help maintain physical function, reduce the risk of injury, and enhance the quality of life by keeping the body mobile and comfortable.

Combining frog hops and reverse bear crawls in a workout routine can offer several benefits- allow me to explain…. 

✨Full-Body Workout: Frog hops engage your lower body, while reverse bear crawls work your upper body and core. Together, they provide a comprehensive full-body workout. 

✨Strength and Endurance: Frog hops build leg strength and explosive power, while reverse bear crawls improve upper body and core strength. This combo enhances both strength and endurance. 

✨Agility and Coordination: These exercises require coordination and balance, enhancing your overall agility. ✨Cardiovascular Fitness: The dynamic nature of these movements can elevate your heart rate, improving cardiovascular fitness. 

✨Core Stability: Reverse bear crawls challenge your core muscles, helping to improve stability and posture. ✨Functional Movement: These exercises mimic natural movements like crawling and jumping, promoting functional fitness. 

✨Versatility: You can modify the intensity and incorporate variations to suit your fitness level and goals. ✨Fat Burning: The combination of strength and cardio elements can help with fat loss. 

❌Remember to perform these exercises with proper form and consult a fitness professional if you’re unsure about your technique or fitness level.
